Five-Year Accident History

Since construction and startup operations in 1972 there has not been an accidental release of propane, or any other hazardous substance at the Suburban Propane Elk Grove Terminal that has resulted in any deaths or offsite injuries, property or environmental damage, evacuations or sheltering in place.  

Emergency Response Program

The Suburban Elk Grove Terminal has developed and maintains a comprehensive Emergency Action Plan (EAP) which details specific procedures to be implemented by site personnel in the event of an emergency, including:

?    Process and equipment shut down procedures;
?    Fire protection procedures;
?    Evacuation procedures;
?    Emergency Responder notification procedures;
?    Public notification procedures;
?    Post-emergency investigation and reporting requirements; and
?    Post-emergency process systems inspection and startup procedures

The Terminal?s EAP has been coordinated with, and is regularly inspected by, local offsite responders, including the Elk Grove Fire Department, the Elk Grove Police Department, the Sacramento County Sheriff?s Department and the Sacramento Metropolitan Fire District.   The Elk Grove Terminal maintains onsite fire-fighting and emergency response systems and equipment to support and augment offsite emergency response resources as well.  The site?s emergency response systems and equipment are maintained in accordance with the site?s accidental release prevention program requirements.

